# Git commits — author as the user

When the user asks you to create a git commit (or you commit after explicit request):

1. **Author identity** — Always pass an explicit author on every commit:
   ```bash
   git commit --author="JacobForges <jacob.adkins@students.maestrocollege.edu>" -m "$(cat <<'EOF'
   Message here.

   EOF
   )"
   ```
   Use this exact name and email unless the user gives a different author in the same thread.

2. **Never** commit with author/committer names or emails containing `Cursor`, `cursoragent`, `cursor.com`, or generic bot identities.

3. **Do not** add `Co-authored-by: Cursor <cursoragent@cursor.com>` (or any Cursor co-author trailer) to commit messages. GitHub shows that as a second author even when the git author is you. Use a plain message body only.

4. **Do not** run `git config` (global or local) to change `user.name` / `user.email` — per-commit `--author` only.

5. If `git log -1` after commit shows the wrong author, amend only when your commit rules allow, still using the same `--author` flag.

6. **Push** only when the user asks; commits should still use the user author before push so GitHub attributes work to **JacobForges**.

If GitHub does not link commits to the profile, the user may need to add `jacob.adkins@students.maestrocollege.edu` as a verified email on GitHub (or supply their `id+login@users.noreply.github.com` noreply address for future commits).
